Rating: 2
I have to say that this recipe is very mediocre. I'm going to stick with my usual easy weeknight Mexican-American meal. For my recipe, see below. It's the most processed meal that I ever eat, but it's delicious. I should say that when you take out the chicken to reduce the sauce, it will look like A LOT of sauce. However, do not make the same mistake I made and reduce the sauce too much, because when you go to put the chicken back in, you'll find that it becomes very dry. I think that it's nice to throw in some corn near the end of the cooking. My recipe: Begin cooking a package of Lipton's Spanish style rice. Preheat oven to 400, and heat oil in large non-stick skillet. Add 1 package ground turkey with 2 or 3 gloves minced garlic and thoroughly chop up as it browns. As it's about halfway browned, add salt, black pepper, corriander, cumin, chili powder, cayenne, red pepper flakes, and fresh lime juice to taste. (It'll seem like a lot of spices) Then add a can of drained diced tomatoes, a can of minced jalepeno chiles, and a can of corn. Layer on tortilas over rice, top with taco sauce and cheese, roll up, and line up in casserole dish. Top with more cheese and cover with tinfoil. Place in a 400 degree oven and cook until the filing is bubbling. Remove foil and brown the edges of the tortillas. Eat.

